
Part 1: Prompt Design & Iteration

1.1 Scenario A: Technical Explanation

Initial Prompt (V1):
Explain neural networks.
V1 LLM Output:
A neural network is a computer system loosely inspired by how the brain works.
Your brain is made of billions of neurons — tiny cells that pass electrical signals to each other. When you learn something (like recognising your friend's face), certain neurons fire together repeatedly until that pattern gets "wired in." Neural networks on computers mimic this idea, but with math instead of biology.
The basic structure:
A neural network has layers of simple mathematical units (also called neurons or nodes):
Input layer — receives raw data (e.g. pixel values of an image)
Hidden layers — where the actual "thinking" happens; each layer extracts increasingly abstract patterns
Output layer — produces the final answer (e.g. "this is a cat")
Each connection between neurons has a weight — a number that says how important that signal is. Learning is just the process of adjusting those weights.
How it learns:
The network makes a prediction
It compares that prediction to the correct answer and measures how wrong it was (the "loss")
It works backward through the layers adjusting weights to reduce that error — a process called backpropagation
Repeat this millions of times on millions of examples, and the weights gradually converge on something useful
Why they work so well:
The key insight is that stacking many layers lets the network learn hierarchies of features automatically. For image recognition, early layers might detect edges, middle layers detect shapes, and later layers detect faces or objects — all without anyone explicitly programming those concepts.
Where you see them in practice:
Neural networks are the engine behind image recognition, speech-to-text, language models (like this one), translation, medical diagnosis, and game-playing AI. The largest modern versions — called deep neural networks or foundation models — have billions or even trillions of parameters (weights).
The core idea, though, is always the same: layers of simple operations, trained by feedback, building up to surprisingly complex behaviour.

Refined Prompt (V2):
Explain neural networks to a 10-year-old child using a simple, fun analogy. Avoid technical jargon.
V2 LLM Output:
Imagine you're trying to get really good at a guessing game.
Someone shows you a picture of an animal and asks: "Is this a cat or a dog?"
At first, you just guess randomly. Sometimes you're right, sometimes wrong. But every time you get it wrong, a friend taps you on the shoulder and says "nope, try again." So you start paying attention — you notice that cats have pointy ears, dogs have floppy tongues, cats look grumpy, dogs look excited. After seeing hundreds of pictures and getting lots of shoulder taps, you get really, really good at it.
A neural network does the exact same thing — except instead of you, it's a computer program. Instead of eyes, it looks at numbers. And instead of a friend tapping your shoulder, it uses math to figure out where it went wrong.
The "network" part just means it's a big chain of tiny helpers passing information along, like a game of telephone — each helper makes the message a little clearer until the last one shouts out the final answer.
The cool part? Nobody tells it what to look for. It figures out the clues all by itself, just by seeing enough examples and being told when it's wrong.
That's how your phone recognises your face, how voice assistants understand what you say, and how computers can now write stories and answer questions — they've all just played the guessing game billions of times.
Final Prompt (V3):
You are a fun and enthusiastic teacher explaining science to curious 10-year-olds. Explain what a neural network is using the analogy of a team of friends learning to recognise dog breeds by looking at lots of photos together. Use short sentences, simple words, and include one "wow fact" at the end.
V3 LLM Output (Final):

Okay class, gather round! 🐶
Imagine you and five friends are playing a game.
Someone puts a photo on the table. Is it a Golden Retriever? A Poodle? A Husky? You all have to guess!
At first, everyone just shouts random answers. You're wrong a LOT. But then something cool happens — every time you guess wrong, your teacher says "nope!" and shows you the right answer.
So you start looking more carefully.
Your friend Maya notices fluffy ears. Your friend Rohan spots curly fur. You notice the colour of the nose. Everyone is picking up different clues!
After seeing hundreds and hundreds of photos, something amazing happens. You all get really, really good at it. You stop guessing. You just know.
A neural network works exactly like your team of friends.
Each "friend" is a tiny piece of the computer program. Each one looks for different clues. They pass what they notice along to the next friend. And at the end, the last friend shouts out the answer.
The more photos it sees, the better it gets. Just like you!
Nobody tells it what clues to look for. It figures that out all by itself. Pretty cool, right?

⚡ WOW FACT: The neural network inside your phone's camera has looked at millions of faces — and it can recognise YOUR face in less time than it takes you to blink! 😲

